You can sort of think of all of your knowledge as being a giant list of facts (this is not at all how the brain works but it will make the analogy simpler). As you navigate the world you pick up more facts and cross out facts and edit facts. This collection of facts is your understanding of the world. 

However, there is this additional program in your mind that sifts through each fact and goes, "is this a fact about me?" and then decides whether or not it should get a little "me" tag. All of the facts that are labeled "me" compose your self-image. 

Self-realization is not the end of acquiring or seeking knowledge itself, which is just curiosity. Nor is it the end of knowledge entirely. Self-realization is realizing that it makes no sense to have a "me" label in the first place, because there is no "me" that is apart from the world. Now the additional program gets closed permanently and all the tags are automatically removed along with the program closing. 

This process is what Jamie means by "self-knowledge just becomes knowledge".

I recently experienced self-realization (literally yesterday). Just going to share the thoughts I had right before the realization and then some other observations I had after the realization. 

Visual perception does not contain objects. You do not exist in visual perception because all that exists is visual qualia (this was while I was looking at a computer screen so it felt incredibly intuitive). It is not possible to see yourself, all you see is vision. Thoughts are essentially just another sense perception right? [click] Oh all that exists in thought is just thought qualia. You can't think about yourself you can only think about thoughts, and clearly you aren't a thought so you can't think about yourself.

The truth is that even though I know that the realization causes the on-going state of emotional peace, me and even Jamie really know very little about what specific preconditions cause the realization to occur beyond "just realizing it bro".

After that I walked back and forth sort of staring at the sky wondering why this took so long to realize when it's literally so simple. To be fair the simplicity is precisely what makes it hard. My experience became more pure, like instead of seeing other people and wondering what they might think of me I just see people. In terms of the ability to think, and even the ability to consider what other people may think of you are completely unchanged.

I did begin to notice that I perceived like a weightless solid block in my head, that has been slowly rounding its corners. This might have something to do with a physical change in the brain but I have no idea whether the change is actually where I perceive the block to be. This block has slowly gotten smaller, and it feels like its presence sort of anchors my mind to the present moment, and any attempt to escape is impossible because the block "blocks" me. This may be similar to Jamie's swirling crater.
